transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling Viagra. This is Olivia speaking. Who do I have the pleasure of speaking with here?

Speaker 2: Kenneth Frank.

Speaker 1: Hi Kenneth, how are you?

Speaker 2: I was okay, so I received another order from—

Speaker 1: Govo meds. I didn't sign up for an automatic—

Speaker 2: refill. I—

Speaker 1: Did a one-time prescription. I—

Speaker 2: I don't know why sending me more pills.

Speaker 1: Yeah, so I can look into this for you.

Speaker 2: What, you want the RX number?

Speaker 1: No, what is the phone number—

Speaker 2: associated with the prescription?

Speaker 1: 774-292-1528.

Speaker 2: Okay, great, and what's your date of birth, Kenneth?

Speaker 1: Five thirty sixty six.

Speaker 2: Okay, that's not what we have. You said five thirty sixty six—

Speaker 1: Well, for—

Speaker 2: What do you have there? I probably put a fake one down.

Speaker 1: Well, that's not good.

Speaker 2: But it sounds—well, I don't—you usually don't put info over the phone. That's probably why, but—

Speaker 1: Right. I can give you my name and address. Kenneth Bryant.

Speaker 2: Yeah, I've seen 80 South Street, Bridgewater.

Speaker 1: 1980 South Street, Bridgewater.

Speaker 2: Yeah.

Speaker 1: Okay. Yeah, so I do see your prescription here.

Speaker 2: Yeah, I mean if you don't want to receive—

Speaker 1: Regular refills, those bi-monthly with your prescription.

Speaker 2: You certainly don't have to. You always have the option to place the prescription on hold—

Speaker 1: For up to six months at a time, just because six months is when the prescription—

Speaker 2: Would expire if we didn't refill it. And the way that would work—

Speaker 1: Is if you did want to place it on hold, say you would still have the option to order in the next six months.

Speaker 2: You just have to give us a call to place the order yourself.

Speaker 1: Now I want to cancel this prescription.

Speaker 2: Okay, so the pills, they don't work for you?

Speaker 1: No.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Okay, I'm sorry to hear that. Well, in that case, that does make sense.

Speaker 2: The last part of my job is to let you know that if the pills don't work for you—

Speaker 1: It looks like you do qualify—

Speaker 2: For a free sample of their newest highest quality product because you haven't tried it.

Speaker 1: No, no, thank you.

Speaker 2: Okay, it comes with a five-month free trial.

Speaker 1: It would be 10.

Speaker 2: I'm not interested.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: Just keep us in mind. We are the only sellers of that product in the entire world.

Speaker 1: We—I want to get a lot of my question, my question, my question for you is why was I—

Speaker 2: Put on an automatic refill when I didn't sign up for that?

Speaker 1: Yeah, so I usually avoid—

Speaker 2: answering that because I—

Speaker 1: Don't want to activate anybody, but when you signed up online—

Speaker 2: There was an agreement that you made where it did state in writing—

Speaker 1: With your prescription, the doctor will subscribe—

Speaker 2: Will prescribe you refills. If you want to make changes to those, call this number, and it was this number—

Speaker 1: Right, for us to call directly. And because we didn't hear from you and you did agree to that—

Speaker 2: The doctor sets up a prescription refill based on the number of pills you ordered, and since you ordered 25—

Speaker 1: It is safe and appropriate for the pharmacy to send those every two months according to them, unless you call—

Speaker 2: Let us know. Hey, how much—how much was I—how much was I charged for that?

Speaker 1: The exact same price as you were the very first prescription, which is $113.95 for 25 pills.

Speaker 2: No, I—I would like a refund and I will return these.

Speaker 1: Yeah, that's fine. Of course, you can do that.

Speaker 2: Okay, so I can email you the directions for how to do that. The email we have on file is—

Speaker 1: K is in Kenneth Bryant.

Speaker 2: 1980 at Comcast.net. Is that accurate?

Speaker 1: It is.

Speaker 2: Okay, great. So yeah, once—

Speaker 1: We receive the product back, of course, we can refund it, and you have a 90-day window, which is great.

Speaker 2: Yeah, so that, you know, I'm gonna send you—it’s gonna say return and refund—

Speaker 1: Instructions, so just keep your eye out.

Speaker 2: Will you cancel the prescription please starting right immediately?

Speaker 1: Yeah, I can do that for you.

Speaker 2: Return and refund—

Speaker 1: Instructions.

Speaker 2: So, yeah, just keep us in mind. We are the only FDA-approved third-party tested—

Speaker 1: Company that sells that product in the entire world.

Speaker 2: And it is a great—

Speaker 1: Product. We'd love to have you back to order some. We just wouldn't be able to offer you a free sample at a later date.

Speaker 2: But I hope you have a great day, Kenneth.

Speaker 1: Well, did you cancel the prescription?

Speaker 2: Yes, why would I tell you that I did and not—why could I get a confirmation number? Would you like to ask me?

Speaker 1: Could I get a confirmation number?

Speaker 2: We don't have those, but your prescription is definitely canceled and I'm looking at it right now.

Speaker 1: Okay, could you email me something that states that?

Speaker 2: Um, no, but the prescription is definitely canceled and these calls are recorded.

Speaker 1: All right, good employee I am. That's true.

Speaker 2: All right, no for an answer. All right. Bye. Bye.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I can, I think.
